%S A397830 10,12,14,20,21,29,30,37,58,64,71,93,100,104,107,142,196,200,247,253,
%T A397830 279,300,343,364,413,481,499,537,557,637,751,787,1000,1002,1038,1063,
%U A397830 1471,1502,1736,1763,2000,2001,2247,2262,2557,2829,2942,3000,3004,3064,3164
%N A397830 Integers k>9 such that removing the most and the least significant digit from k^2 produces another square.
%C A397830 If we repeat the process two times 107 is the first integer which produces two squares: 107^2 = 11449 -> 144 = 12^2 -> 4 = 2^2.
%C A397830 From _David A. Corneth_, Jul 17 2026: (Start)
%C A397830 No terms ends in 5. If a(n) ends in 0 then a(n) is of the form d*10^m where d in {1, 2, 3} and m >= 1.
%C A397830 Looking at squares of the form 60*m^2 + 1 I get m in 4, 248, 15372, 952816, ... which are multiples of 4. Dividing by 4 gives 1, 62, 3843, 238204, ... which has partial sums A180926 for first few terms. Does this provide a family of terms? (End)
%H A397830 David A. Corneth, <a href="/A397830/b397830.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..186</a>
%e A397830 37^2 = 1369 -> 36 = 6^2;
%e A397830 279^2 = 77841 -> 784 = 28^2;
%e A397830 4136^2 = 17106496 -> 710649 = 843^2.
%t A397830 Select[Range[10, 10^5], IntegerQ[Sqrt[FromDigits[IntegerDigits[#^2][[2 ;; -2]]]]] &] (* _Paolo Xausa_, Jul 23 2026 *)
%o A397830 (PARI) is(n) = {if(n < 10, return(0)); my(s = n^2, qd = #Str(s)); issquare((s\10)%10^(qd - 2))} \\ _David A. Corneth_, Jul 17 2026
%o A397830 (Python)
%o A397830 from math import isqrt
%o A397830 def ok(k): return k > 9 and isqrt(t:=int(str(k**2)[1:-1]))**2 == t
%o A397830 print([k for k in range(4000) if ok(k)]) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Jul 19 2026
